[heard] nQoYJ_00000.mp3: you don't wake up to the sun you wake up to a dull persistent ache in your neck for a moment you forget where you are and then you feel the hard curve of wood beneath you it's the takamakura the unforgiving pillow designed not for comfort but for preservation you sleep on this small lacquered block to protect your hairstyle a complex creation of wax combs and ornaments that must last for an entire week one wrong move in your sleep and you ruin hours of work this is your first lesson of the day and every day beauty is discipline and discipline is pain your day began long before you were you it started when you were just a girl perhaps 10 or 11 years old brought to the okia the geisha house in kyoto's gion district you don't remember much of your old family or maybe you choose not to your name was taken from you and a new one was given one that tied you to the house and your new sisters at first you were just a shikomi a maid you spent your days on your hands and knees scrubbing wooden floors until they shone running errands for the senior geisha and learning the most important skill of all how to be invisible you learned to speak only when spoken to to bow at the correct angle and to understand the unspoken language of a glance or a tapped fan after a year or more of this servitude if the okasan the house mother saw potential in you you became a minarai
